### Command Execution

Prefer absolute paths over `cd <path> &&` to maintain a consistent working directory.

For `gh pr create` and `gh issue create`, pass the body via a heredoc on stdin to avoid
shell escaping issues and argv length limits with complex markdown:

```bash
gh pr create --title "Title" --body-file - <<'EOF'
Body with **markdown** here.
EOF
```

When this repo's pipeline (or any agent skill) needs to file a follow-up issue rather
than logging it in scrollback or a markdown report, it calls `flow-create-issue` from a
**named site only** — see the per-skill SKILL.md docs and the relevant exemption entry in
this file's "Don'ts" section. Auto-issue-creation from arbitrary skills is forbidden;
adding a new fire site requires a named exemption in `## Don'ts` first.

### Committing

- Split logically isolated work into separate commits. Don't over-split trivial changes.
- Short imperative summary ≤50 chars (renders as PR title).
- **Write a descriptive body** — not just a one-liner. The body should explain **why** the
  change was made, not restate the diff. Include:
  - The problem or motivation (what prompted this change).
  - Non-obvious design choices and their rationale (why this approach, not others).
  - When relevant, what was tried and **didn't** work, and why — so future agents don't
    repeat dead ends (e.g. "tried X first but it broke Y because Z").
  - Any follow-up or known limitations.
  - Exception: trivial, self-evident changes (typo fixes, dependency bumps, formatting) may
    omit the body.
- Pass multi-line messages via heredoc to preserve formatting:

  ```bash
  git commit -F - <<'EOF'
  short imperative summary

  Why: <motivation>
  Approach: <non-obvious choices + rationale>
  Tried: <what didn't work, if relevant>
  EOF
  ```

- `git commit`, `push`, `checkout`, `switch`, `branch` (create) are safe on non-default branches.

